{"/service/ndnp/okhi/batch_okhi_ham_ver01/data/sn86090528/00295864667/1920112701/0648.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nCHICKASHA DAILY EXPRESS, CHICKASHA, OKLAHOMA, SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 27, 1920.\nChickasha Daily Express\nEO. II. EVANS Publisher and Business Manager\nJ- EDWIN POOL Managing Editor\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF GRADY COUNTY\nEntered at th Postoffiee at Chickasha, Oklahoma, aa second clans\nmail matter v r\nCHICKASHA, OKLAHOMA, SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 27, 1920.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES Any erroneous reflections on\nOne yr. delivered by carrier $6.00 the character of any person,\nSix months $3.00 firm or corporation and any\nI hree months $1.50 misstatement which may ap-\nOne month .60 pear in the columns of the\nOne year by mall... $4.00 Express will be gladly Cor-\nSix month by mail 2.00 rected upon its being brought\nThree months by mail 1.00 to the attention of the\nSingle copy So management.\nGives All The Local News aff$'$tjx 'News By U. P. Wire Daily.\nEXPRESS PACKAGETTES\nFour things a man must leai'n to do\nIf he would make li in record true:\nTo think without confusion clearly;\nTo love his fellow-men sincerely;\nTo act Irom hone.st motives purely;\nTo trust in God and heaven securely.\nHenry Van Dyke.\nBefore he gets through with the\njob, Mr. Harding will find that to\nform his \"new association of nations\"\nrequires more than a simple twist\nof his wrist.\nAccording to the editor of the Ea-\nld News, who Is an authority on\netiquette, it is improper for a young\nlady to ask a gentleman for a dance.\nHowever, we suppose, the law il\nlows a little lattitude for Leap Year, j\nft\nCredit Contraction and Business Depression.\nA big, robust and, to nil appearances, healthy man developed\nsome symptoms which prompted him to consult a physician. To\nllie untrained eye there was nothing wrong with him; indeed, he\npresented a perfect picture of health, llie hectic flush in his face\nvi 1 1 raci ing no attention, liti,t when the doctor took his temperature,\nthumped his chest and took a look at his \"insides\" with the X-rays,\nthere was a different story to tell. The physician discovered lliat\nthe man had a malady which, if unchecked, must prove fatal hut\nwhich, if given proper trVatnient, would have Jess serious conse\nquences, the palient being assured of recovery. It was a heavy blow\n1o tie man who was engaged in a prosperous business; he didn't\nlike it lie idea of being put to bed, as the treatment demanded, but\nhe finally decided to lake the doctor's advice.\nNow that big. healthy-looking man was the business of the\ncountry, which, but a few months ago, was in the must flourishing\ncondition ever known, but the doctors knew that a m'aladj' which\nwould end in a disastrous panic was working on it. The patient\nwas going the pace that kills. There was hugely expanded credit,\ntm \"orgie\" of spending, extra vaangce and speculation, which must\ncveii! ually bring on a catastrophe. It was decided that contraction\nof credit would save the patient and the federal reserve board adop\nled that method of treatment. The treatment probably caused more\nsuffering than either the palient or physicians anticipated but it\nprevented a fatal panic and, with all the woes caused by deflation,\nllie patient is on the way to recovery and sound health.\nThe foregoing view of the policy adopted by the federal re\nserve board is held by many eminent financial authorities and it is\nmore fully set forth by the Dallas News in the following editorial:\n\"Doubtless the business depression which now afflicts the\ncountry would not have come upon it when it did if the banks had\ncontinued to extend credit in the liberal, not to say the improvi\ndent, way they had been doing.. We should all have gone on buy\ning as Ave ditl when, if one could not earn enough to satisfy his de\nsires, he could make up the deficit by buying on credit; or with\nmoney borrowed to supplement his earnings. When the banks\nslopped exchanging money for notes of hand, without much if any\nregard for the uses to be made of the money, and began to insist\non a liquidation of notes which they bad already cashed, they put\nthe brakes on business, with the resulting jar and slowing down\nlliat are now the occasion of so much complaint. a had hen to\nbe content with such things as we could buy with our (arnings,\nwhich means that we had to dispense with those things ,ve had been\nbuying on credit or with borrowed money. The sudden I-'fs of in\ndulgences to which we had become habituated during the profligate\nyears of the war was painful to those who suffered it, a; d to these\nwho hail adjusted their businesses to the demands of those extrav\nagances. These discomfitures are chargeable, at least in a large de\ngree, to. the action of the banks in substituting a policy of credit\ncontraction lor one ot credit expansion.\nPut the action of the banks in doing that only hastened the\ncoming of the business depression the country now feels. It did not\ncause it. It is the product of economic, forces mightier than the\ncombined power 6f the banks. It must have come of its own mo\nmentum, and irresistibly albeit not quite so soon as it did if Ire\nbanks had continued their policy of credit expansion. ,?ut vhjn it\ndid come, it would have come with a vastly more destructive force.\nThere is a limit to the lending power of the banks, a. limit to the\nheight of the structure which can safely be reared upon the founda\ntion of wealth, made up of goods and property. How nearly the\nliberal credit operations of the banks brought us to that limit, only\na few men are competent to say; but that we had come into sight\nof the danger signals must be pretty evident. Had the banks ignor\ned them, they might have deferred llie coming of the depression\nnow felt, but they could not bine prevented its arrival. And when\nit did arrive, it would have gathered the cyclonic fury of a panic,\nsuch as Japan, Argentina, Brazil and other countries have suffered,\nonly that ours would probably have been a much worse one. Hence\nthere is no reason to complain of the banks for doing what thev did.\nIt would be much more reasonable io complain of them for not hav\ning done it sooner. The criticism that they indulged the country\nin its extravagances and speculations too long, with the result that\nthe contraction of credit had to be brought about too abruptly, is\none which they would find it hard to answer. Hut to complain of\n1 hem for not having continued to indulge the country is 1o utter a\ncriticism which is at once unjust and foolish.\nA Kentucky man who was arrest\ned in Dallas confessed that he had\nembezzled some seven hundred thou\nsand dollars but aside from that,\n\"\"'jgafe\"\"''\"\nf j\"?\nif\nHead of Committee marriage licenses.\nProbing Ship Scandal Marriage licenses were issued yex-\ni terday to:\nF. llraili y, ag 2 1. of Oklaho r.u\nCity, and Minn HmkhIp Walls, aire T'.\nof Tattle. 1\nE. W. Caldwell, age J I, of Straf\nford, and Miss Vannle McCliire, age\nSI, of Lucille. I\nAlvlu 1j. Lowe, nga 21, of Chick-\naslia, and Miss Catherine 1.. Chu\n1\nman, age 22, of .Chit-kasha.\nl'aul James, ago 22, of Vinson, and\nMiss Ruhy Langstoii, age 2:!, of\nChickasha.\nJohn Calvin HoydjUon, age 2:',, of\nWashita, and Miss (Jladys li inilr\nHeiney, age 2.\"i, of Washita.\nThe Brailey-Wal.ts and I Caldwell\nMcClure ceremonies wera performed\nby T. V. Moore, justice of the pca.Mi.\nw\nand insure that prop-\nerty before it is too!\nlate. i\n,C. B. March\nhoa M\nJOSl'Jl'H WAIjttil\nSensational disclosures of graft\nnml pxtravae-nnt. wawfo in the onera-\nhe said his conscience was clear. A ()f the Merchallt M:lrine have 2(l-2t\nbeen made before the Congressional\nentative Joseph Walsh, of Massa-\nGREAT REDUCTION SALE\nON STOVES\nWe will give onc-ioiirih off for\ncash on all cook stoves and heating\nstoves for the next :!0 days, so 1\nyou need a stove don't fall to supply\nyour needs.\nnt'IIO WALLACE.\n0 1y Bid.\n!II!I!l!!!!li!!!ll!!ll!!lilii!!!llf\nsort of model citizen, you might say\nbut a cold world will probably not\nforgive him for his little act of indiscretion.\nflubbed into the Uin tor rheumu\nChickasha is a better town than\nTulsa. Proof: Didn't our football\nteam capture second place in the\nconference while' the big oil town\nhad to be content with third?\nBesides that, just think what the\nChickasha team did to Guthrie in\ndie tin key day \"track meet.\"\nFurthermore, some excellent an\nthorities hold that it is not \"good\nform,\" for a tobacco borrower to\nspeak disparingly of the brand his\nfriend smokes.\nSi Simp says he notices that ho\nalways loses a lot of sleep when he\nays up late at night.\nAs a rule, about ths third day af\nter Thanksgiving, the man of the\nhouse is in a mood to be grateful\nbecause the turkpy iisn't going to\nlast much longer.\nWhen a man's wife begins to in\nsist that he learn to dance, in most\ncases it is only a matter of time\ntill he surrenders.\nAnd our observation has been that\nthis poetry-of-motion bug bites a man\nwho is well along in life, it doesn't\nInvestigating Committee. Itepres-j -Ism, neuralgia, contractec' musci\nchiuetts is head of the committee,\nwhich has been probing the scandal\nbut he said Weep not; she Is not\ndead, but sleepelh.\nAnd they laugh al him to scorn,\nknowing that she was dead.\nAnd he put them, all out, and took\nher. by the hand, and called, saying.\nMaid, arise.\nAnd her spirit ciinri a?ain, and\nshe arose straightway; and hr; com\nmanded to give her meat.\nAnd her parents were astonished:\nbut he Adiarged them that, thoy\nshould tell no man what was done.\niprains or lameness. Mallard's Snow\n'.iniinent goes right through trie\ntesh to the bone, easl'ig pain and\n'moving the cause. It is a powerful\nmin relief. Three sizes, .Tic, f.Oe and\n3.20 per bottle. Sold by Wren Drur\no.\nDOES YOUR ROOF LEAK?\nWe absolutely stop leaks in any\nroof, shiiiL'b's, tin or paper.\nI. L. SMITH Phono 1341.\nDON'T PHONE\ntake long for 